{
  "doc_id": "4396",
  "text": "Kernouvé is an ordinary chondrite of the H group from an observed fall in France in 1869. It is texturally metamorphosed and of petrologic type 6. It contains abundant metals, was heated for a significant period of time before the onset of partial melting, and is minimally shocked [CITATION_1] . It contains relict chondrules set in a coarse-grained, recrystallized matrix of olivine (Fo 80 ), orthopyroxene (Fs 15.7À18.1 ), plagioclase, Fe-Ni metal, troilite, chromite and phosphate [CITATION_2] . Chromite grains from this chondrite are chemically homogeneous and have the typical equilibrated H-chondritic composition with generally somewhat lower TiO 2 (~2.5 wt.%) and higher Al 2 O 3 (~6.0 wt.%) contents than equilibrated L chondrites (typically TiO 2 3.0 wt.% and Al 2 O 3~5 .2 wt.%) [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] .",
